The Justice Department concluded that Attorney General John Ashcroft did not violate anti-lobbying laws while promoting the Patriot Act.
The Act, passed after 9/11, expanded law enforcement powers against terrorists.
Renewal of the Act and FBI reform are key issues.
Critics find the Act's surveillance powers intrusive.
A coalition seeks to repeal certain provisions, citing concerns about privacy and civil liberties.
President Bush and Attorney General Gonzales advocate for renewing the Act, emphasizing the importance of balancing security and freedom.
The debate over the Act's renewal highlights the ongoing tension between national security and individual rights.
